Part I - Prosper Loan Data Exploration¶

by Elliot Manuel Sithole¶

29-09-2022

Introduction¶

Prosper Marketplace, Inc. is a San Francisco, California-based company involved in the peer-to-peer lending industry. Prosper Funding LLC, one of its subsidiaries, operates Prosper.com, a website where individuals can either invest in personal loans or request to borrow money.The Propser loan data set contains 113,937 loan entries with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate, current loan status, borrower income, and many others. This data dictionary elaborates on the features contained in the data set.

#group using credit lower score cut-offs
def credit_score(c):
    outcome=""
    if c <= 660 :
        outcome = "Poor"
    if c>=660:
        outcome = "Fair"
    if c>=680:
        outcome = "Good"
    if c>=720:
        outcome = "Excellent"
    return outcome
df_clean['credit_score'] = df_clean['credit_score_avg'].apply(credit_score)

def hist2dgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    palette = kwargs.pop('color')
    plt.hist2d(x, y, cmap = palette, cmin = 0.5)

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The strength of the correlation between borrower rate and borrower ARP seems not to be affected by any other features assessed in the data set.

Higher credit scores appears to have a significant effect in lowering borrower rate and APR and so is owning a home.

It seems the longer the loan term the lower the borrower ARP, with five year term often attracting a lower an ARP. Whilst, there is much variability in ARP at shorter 1 year terms but higher borrower ARPs.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

During the bivaiate exploratory analysis, interestingly the employed category had a high borrower-APR than self-employed and not-employed groups. It turns out that on multivariate analysis the not employed status had in fact fewer data points to validate association with lower borrower APR.

From the plots, it doesn't seem like there's a systematic interaction effect between some of the observed categorical features. However, it can be argued that some of the features aren't fully independent, and also given that a lot of features were not analysed, further exploration maybe warranted.
